 Briefly summarize C++ data types with examples — list of data types with examples

Fundamental (built-in) types:

bool — boolean values: true, false.
Example: bool flag = true;

char — character type (usually 1 byte).
Example: char c = 'A';

signed char, unsigned char — small integer types for raw bytes.

int — integer (signed).
Example: int i = -42;

short, long, long long — integer types with different ranges.
Example: long long big = 900000000000LL;

unsigned variants — only nonnegative values (e.g. unsigned int n = 10u;).

float, double, long double — floating-point numbers.
Example: double x = 3.14159;

wchar_t, char16_t, char32_t — wide/Unicode character types.


Derived & compound types:

Pointers: int* p = &i; (store memory addresses).

References: int& r = i; (alias to another object).

Arrays: int a[5] = {1,2,3,4,5};

Function types / pointers: int (*fn)(int);


User-defined types:

struct / class / union: group data + behavior.
Example:

struct Employee {
  std::string name;
  int age;
  double salary;
};
Employee e{"Alice", 30, 5000.0};

enum / enum class: enumerations.
Example: enum class Color { Red, Green, Blue };


Standard library types (commonly used):

std::string — dynamic string type. Example: std::string s = "hello";

std::vector<T> — dynamic array. Example: std::vector<int> v = {1,2,3};

std::map<Key,Value>, std::unordered_map<Key,Value> — associative containers.

Smart pointers: std::unique_ptr<T>, std::shared_ptr<T> — automatic lifetime management.


Type qualifiers and modifiers:

const — read-only after initialization. Example: const int N = 10;

volatile — value might change outside program flow (rare).

static (in various contexts) — internal linkage or extended lifetime.

mutable — allows modification in const contexts (member fields).


Example demonstrating several types together:

#include <string>
#include <vector>

struct Person {
    std::string name;
    int age;
};

int main() {
    const int MAX = 100;
    std::vector<Person> roster;
    roster.push_back({"Sam", 21});
    roster.push_back({"Maya", 22});
    return 0;
}


